cs.NI, cs.DC, cs.SY, cs.IT, cs.LG

This paper is likely to belong to the arXiv CS sub-category of cs.NI (Networking and Internet Architecture) as it deals with mobile-edge computation offloading, which involves the interaction between mobile devices and nearby servers such as base stations. It may also belong to cs.DC (Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing) as it involves resource management for offloading computation to nearby servers. Additionally, it may belong to cs.SY (Systems and Control) as it deals with optimizing resource management policies. It may also belong to cs.IT (Information Theory) as it involves data transmission and partitioning. Finally, it may belong to cs.LG (Machine Learning) as it uses the block coordinate decent method for computing the optimal resource-management policy.
